{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c3340818-a031-47be-9aeb-58dad6886599","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, VS Code, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or the [dotnet-monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) container image instead.\n- For production, prefer `dotnet-monitor` — it exposes an HTTP API for on-demand trace collection without exec'ing in.\n- If you need OS-level detail (kernel + managed stacks), use `dotnet-trace` with `--format speedscope` or consider **`perf`** but that requires `SYS_ADMIN` / `privileged` capabilities on the container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bd9a23e6-4576-49fb-9791-980b9fb07311","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"9425:20C30D:18A9592:1BF4561:69E81E97"},"id":"06d0acd2-9fd4-4319-b3f1-775130d7d095","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:04:34.570Z","parentId":"dc6c362b-3714-4740-b394-eb6783096e0d"}
